434
47:46.830 --> 47:50.220
and again, it's a promise problem.

435
47:50.220 --> 47:58.380
This time, the promise is that there exists some n bits string s for which the function f
works as you see right here,

436
47:58.380 --> 48:05.011
where the output is given
by the binary dot product of the input with this string s,

437
48:05.011 --> 48:12.270
and the goal is simply
to find the string s. So we can imagine that the
string s is hidden in some sense,

438
48:12.270 --> 48:19.380
but we can learn about it
by making queries to f, and our goal is to find
this hidden string.

439
48:19.380 --> 48:28.830
To be clear, most functions
won't satisfy this promise, but as usual, we only care about the
input functions that do.

440
48:28.830 --> 48:35.310
As it turns out, the Deutsch-Jozsa circuit actually solves this problem
right out of the box.

441
48:35.310 --> 48:42.900
If we run it for a
function like we have here that satisfies the
promise for some string s, the measurements will reveal the string s

442
48:42.900 --> 48:47.430
with no post-processing required.

443
48:47.430 --> 48:50.910
So let's see how this works.

444
48:50.910 --> 48:56.400
We've already analyzed
the Deutsch-Jozsa circuit, so we can actually just
skip right to the end.

445
48:56.400 --> 49:06.570
Here's the expression that we
had from before for the state just prior to the measurements, and that expression was
valid for any function f.

446
49:06.570 --> 49:14.230
And now, if we substitute
in what we're promised about the function f and simplify,

447
49:14.230 --> 49:20.130
we get the minus state
for the bottom qubit tensored with cat s for the top n qubits.

448
49:20.130 --> 49:24.630
And so we get s when we measure.

449
49:24.630 --> 49:30.630
There is some work to do to perform the simplifications
that I've shown here, and I won't go through that in this video,

450
49:30.630 --> 49:37.890
but there is more detail about it in the textbook content for this series, which you can find by following the link in the description of the video,

451
49:37.890 --> 49:43.140
or just try it for
yourself for some practice.

452
49:43.140 --> 49:52.050
So what we found is that
the Deutsch-Jozsa circuit solves the Bernstein-Vazirani
problem with a single query.

453
49:52.050 --> 49:58.710
It's not too hard to show
that any classical algorithm, whether it's deterministic
or probabilistic, needs at least n queries

454
49:58.710 --> 50:04.770
to solve the Bernstein-Vazirani problem for the simple reason that we need n bits of
information to recover s,

455
50:04.770 --> 50:09.330
and each query gives us at
most 1 bit of information.

456
50:09.330 --> 50:16.050
So we get another advantage of quantum over classical
query algorithms, one query for quantum algorithms,

457
50:16.050 --> 50:20.610
n queries for classical algorithms.

458
50:20.610 --> 50:28.560
It's worth taking just a moment to speak about the
nomenclature that's used in the context of this problem and a little bit about the history.

459
50:28.560 --> 50:37.230
People sometimes refer to the algorithm that I just described as being the Bernstein-Vazirani algorithm, but it's really just the
Deutsch-Jozsa circuit,

460
50:37.230 --> 50:42.898
and that's something that was,
in fact, very clearly stated in Bernstein and Vazirani's work.

461
50:42.898 --> 50:49.680
So it is a little bit strange that it's called the
Bernstein-Vazirani algorithm because it's pretty much the same thing as the Deutsch-Jozsa algorithm

462
50:49.680 --> 50:55.080
minus the post-processing. Bernstein and Vazirani did,
however, go a step further.

463
50:55.080 --> 51:01.710
They defined a recursive
version of this problem, where you basically
have to solve instances of the Bernstein-Vazirani problem

464
51:01.710 --> 51:07.560
to unlock new instances of the problem that are arranged in a
complicated tree-like pattern.

465
51:07.560 --> 51:14.880
It's a highly contrived problem, but the point is that by
defining a problem in this way, they could effectively stretch out

466
51:14.880 --> 51:19.710
the one versus n query separation between quantum and classical.

467
51:19.710 --> 51:29.220
And what they obtained is
the very first known example of a so-called super polynomial advantage of quantum over probabilistic algorithms.

468
51:29.220 --> 51:37.950
This recursive version of the
Bernstein-Vazirani problem also turned out much later
to be very interesting in computational complexity
theory for different reasons.

469
51:37.950 --> 51:44.640
Anyway, the point is that
Bernstein and Vazirani certainly deserve recognition for their important contributions,

470
51:44.640 --> 51:53.040
but it really doesn't make
sense to refer to this as the Bernstein-Vazirani algorithm, it's basically just the
Deutsch-Jozsa algorithm.

471
51:53.040 --> 51:59.550
In the last part of the lesson, we'll take a look at one
more quantum query algorithm known as Simon's algorithm.

472
51:59.550 --> 52:07.170
You'll see a clear similarity
between this algorithm and the Deutsch-Jozsa algorithm, but it is different, and more importantly,

473
52:07.170 --> 52:13.380
it reveals a much stronger advantage of quantum over classical
query algorithms.

474
52:13.380 --> 52:22.680
Specifically, it gives us a
provable exponential advantage of quantum over classical algorithms, even probabilistic ones.

475
52:22.680 --> 52:30.870
The problem it solves is a bit artificial, and it's hard to imagine a situation in which solving this
problem would be useful,

476
52:30.870 --> 52:37.350
but it did directly inspire
Peter Shor's discovery of a quantum algorithm
for integer factorization,

477
52:37.350 --> 52:46.410
and that very strongly supports
this idea of the query model as a Petri dish in which quantum algorithmic
ideas can be developed.

478
52:46.410 --> 52:56.010
Let's start with the query problem that Simon's algorithm solves, which, as you might have guessed,
is called Simon's problem.

479
52:56.010 --> 53:03.180
Here's a statement of the problem, and we're going to need to unpack it to understand what it's all about.

480
53:03.180 --> 53:09.360
The first thing to
notice is that this time, the input function f maps n
bits strings to m bits strings

481
53:09.360 --> 53:14.460
where m is some positive integer that isn't equal to one in general.

